<h1>From Levi Allen</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">May it please Your Excellency</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Salisbury in Connecticut<br/>Jany 27th 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I have rode some hundred miles in consequence of my brother Ethan Allen (commonly cald Colo. Allen) being taken prisoner near Montreal 25th Sept. last[,] waited on Your Excellency at head-quarters in Cambridge in Decm. last, since that waited on Genl Schuyler on the same business, he read me a paragraph of Your Excellencys letter directing him to enquire what was become of Colo. Allen,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> and desird me if possible to git some evidence of the treatment he met with after taken prisoner, Accordingly have spared neither trouble, or cost to accomplish the same, one affidavet only have been able to Obtain, which here inclose, There is a number of the Ministerial Troops in this and the neighbouring Colonies prisoners, but few of them have seen my brother since a prisoner, only those taken on board the gaspy brigg, and it is next to impossible to git any of them to say Allen or any Other prisoner was used ill for fear of retaliation besides they have been Chargd by Prescott and all the Officers not to mention Allens being put in Irons on pain of deaththe soldier that made the affidavet here inclosd was Very loth and I should not Obtaind it, but he had previously dropt words to the Same import of the affidavet I then brot him before proper Authority and told him he must declare on Oath whether Colo. Allen was put in Irons or not; then he declard on oath what the affidavet Says, at the same time begd none present would mention his name[.]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Have some thoughts of Going to England in cognito after My brother but am not positively certain he is sent there, tho believe he is; beg your Excellency will favour me with a line and acquaint me if any inteligence concerning him, and if your Excellency pleases your Opinion of the expediency of going after him, &amp; whether your
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0196">[196]</span>
Excellency would think proper to Advance any Money for that purpose as My brother was a man blessd with more fortitude than fortune; Your Excellency may think at first thought I can do nothing by going to England, I feel as if could do a great deal, by raising a mob in London bribing the goaler or by giting into some Servile employment with the goaler and Over faithfulness make myself master of the key, or at least be able to lay my hand on it some night; I beg Your Excellency will countenance my going,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> can muster more than one hundred <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">mutilated</span> My Own porperty shall regard Spending that no more than one Copper, Your Excellency must know Allen was not Only a Brother but a Real Friend that Sticketh closer than a brother, Have Two brothers in the Continental Army one a Capt. the Other a Lieut. the latter with the army before Quebeck whither he is there now or with Genl M<span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">ontgomery</span> in Heaven cant tell[.]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> we look up to your Excellency as Our political Father and head of a Great People. Your Excellenys most Obedient ever faithful &amp; Very Humb. Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Levi Allen</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>N. B. if your Excellency chuses I should wait on you personally I only wait Your commands Cannot live without going to England if my brother is sent there beg your Excellency wont discover this letter least the Adverse party know my design.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>


   <p>Levi Allen (c.17431801) was a younger brother of Ethan Allen, the former colonel commandant of the Green Mountain Boys. Several weeks after his capture at Montreal, Ethan Allen was sent in chains to Falmouth, England, where he arrived a few days before Christmas. The British soon decided to return him to America, however. On 8 Jan. 1776 Ethan Allen sailed from England in a warship and after stopping at Cork and Madeira arrived on 3 May at Cape Fear, North Carolina. Later that month another warship took him to Halifax, Nova Scotia. Levi Allen did not go to England but continued seeking the release of his brother. Ethan Allen was paroled in New York City in October 1776 and was exchanged in May 1778.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0531" class="document">GW to Schuyler, 18 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Peter Rammon, a soldier in the 26th Regiment of Foot who was captured at Montreal the previous fall, testified in his affidavit dated 19 Jan. 1776 that Some time the latter End of September or forepart of October last past he this deponant was on board the Gaspy brig near Montreal, When a man Called Col. Allen was brought on board, and put in Irons and Continued So for more than thirty days not free from his Irons one minute day or night. . . .
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0197">[197]</span>
And that Said Allen was Very Sick during the Whole time with the Yellow Janders and was Attended by Doctr Huntley Every day (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>George Baylor replied to Levi Allen on 9 Feb.: There is little doubt, but that Colonel Allen has been Sent to England, the General has enquired of General Howe about him, but receivd for answer that his command did not extend to Quebec, &amp; that he knew nothing of your Brotheras to your going to England after him, His Excellency cannot give you any oppinion thereon, he cannot think there would be even a probability of success in your scheme[.] it would be running yourself in danger, without a prospect of rendering Service to your Brother (ibid.).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0141-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Heman Allen (c.17401778) was a captain in the Green Mountain Boys, and Ira Allen (<span class="choice correction" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Corrected from '1752' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2013-02-25]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">1751</span>1814) was a lieutenant in that corps.</p>

</div>
</div>
